Assuming CustomerID is an identity column in the CustomerTbl table, you can retrieve the last inserted CustomerID using the following SQL query:

SELECT IDENT_CURRENT('CustomerTbl')

This query will return the last identity value generated for the specified table, in this case 'CustomerTbl'. You can then use this value to set the value of i to the last CustomerID plus one.

Here's an example of how you can use this query in your C# code:

// Create a SQL connection
SqlConnection connection = new SqlConnection(connectionString);

// Create a SQL command to retrieve the last identity value for the CustomerTbl table
SqlCommand command = new SqlCommand("SELECT IDENT_CURRENT('CustomerTbl')", connection);

// Open the connection
connection.Open();

// Execute the command and retrieve the last identity value
int lastCustomerID = Convert.ToInt32(command.ExecuteScalar());

// Increment the last identity value to get the next CustomerID
int nextCustomerID = lastCustomerID + 1;

// Close the connection
connection.Close(); 

// Set the value of i to the next CustomerID
int i = nextCustomerID;

To make a variable available in one form to all forms, you can use any of the following methods:

1. Public static variable: You can declare a public static variable in a class and assign the value of your variable to it in one form. Then you can access the value of this variable from any form in your application. Here's an example:

   ```csharp
   public static class GlobalVariables
   {
       public static int MyVariable;
   }
   ```

   In one form:

   ```csharp
   GlobalVariables.MyVariable = 10;
   ```

   In another form:

   ```csharp
   int myValue = GlobalVariables.MyVariable;
   ```

2. Application settings: You can store the value of your variable in the application settings and access it from any form. Here's an example:

   In one form:

   ```csharp
   Properties.Settings.Default.MyVariable = 10;
   Properties.Settings.Default.Save();
   ```

   In another form:

   ```csharp
   int myValue = Properties.Settings.Default.MyVariable;
   ```

3. Constructor dependency injection: You can pass the value of your variable to the constructor of each form that requires it. Here's an example:

   In one form:

   ```csharp
   int myValue = 10;
   Form2 myForm = new Form2(myValue);
   myForm.Show();
   ```

   In another form:

   ```csharp
   public partial class Form2 : Form
   {
       private int _myValue;

       public Form2(int myValue)
       {
           InitializeComponent();
           _myValue = myValue;
       }

       // You can use _myValue in your form
   }
   ```

