You cannot access the `Login` form's controls directly from a static class like this. Instead, you should pass the value of the `Login.Name` property as a parameter to the `globalvariable` class. 

Here's an example of how you can modify the `globalvariable` class to accept the `CustomerName` parameter:

```
public static class GlobalVariables
{
    public static string CustomerName { get; set; }
}
```

Then, in your `Login` form, you can set the value of `CustomerName` when the user logs in:

```
private void LoginButton_Click(object sender, EventArgs e)
{
    // Authentication code here...

    if (authenticated)
    {
        GlobalVariables.CustomerName = NameTextBox.Text;
        // Close the login form and show the main form...
    }
}
```

Finally, in your other forms, you can use the `GlobalVariables.CustomerName` property to access the logged-in user's name:

```
string customerName = GlobalVariables.CustomerName;
```

Note that you should only set the value of `CustomerName` in the `Login` form after the user has been authenticated. Also, you should make sure to clear this value when the user logs out or closes the application to avoid using stale data.

If you are getting an error that `GlobalVariables.CustomerName` does not exist in the current context, it's possible that you have not properly included the namespace that contains the `GlobalVariables` class.

Make sure that the class is declared in a namespace, for example:

```
namespace MyApp
{
    public static class GlobalVariables
    {
        public static string CustomerName { get; set; }
    }
}
```

Then, in each file where you want to access the `GlobalVariables` class, you need to add a `using` statement at the top of the file to include the namespace, like this:

```
using MyApp;
```

Once you have added the `using` statement, you should be able to access the `GlobalVariables.CustomerName` property as follows:

```
string customerName = GlobalVariables.CustomerName;
```

If you are still getting an error, make sure that the `GlobalVariables` class is declared as `public` and that it's accessible from the class where you are trying to access it. If the class is `internal`, you will not be able to access it from other classes in your application.
